DISCLOSURE_INFO:
{
  "Initiated By" : "U.S. SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION",
  "Allegations" : "SEC LITIGATION RELEASE 20720A, SEPTEMBER 16, 2008: SECTIONS 10(B) AND 14(E) OF THE SECURITIES EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934 AND RULES 10B-5 AND 14E-3 THEREUNDER - THE SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (\"COMMISSION\" OR \"SEC\") ANNOUNCED TODAY THAT IT FILED A COMPLAINT IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT FOR THE NORTHERN DISTRICT OF ILLINOIS AGAINST LANCE D. MCKEE (\"MCKEE\") AND OTHER THREE INDIVIDUALS (COLLECTIVELY, \"DEFENDANTS\") ALLEGING FRAUD IN CONNECTION WITH INSIDER TRADING IN THE SECURITIES OF A CORPORATION ('COMPANY\") BY THREE INDIVIDUALS WHO RECEIVED TIPS DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY FROM A DEFENDANT. THE SEC ALLEGES THAT A DEFENDANT MISAPPROPRIATED MATERIAL NONPUBLIC INFORMATION FROM HIS BROTHER, A MEMBER OF COMPANY'S BOARD OF DIRECTORS, AND FURTHER ALLEGES THAT ON NOVEMBER 10, 2005, THREE DAYS BEFORE A PUBLIC ANNOUNCEMENT THAT COMPANY HAD AGREED TO BE ACQUIRED BY A CORPORATION (\"CORPORATION\"), A DEFENDANT TIPPED ANOTHER TWO DEFENDANTS, BOTH OF WHOM PURCHASED COMPANY SECURITIES. ONE OF THE DEFENDANT, IN TURN, TIPPED MCKEE, WHO ALSO PURCHASED COMPANY SECURITIES. FURTHER, THE SEC ALLEGES THAT AFTER A DEFENDANT TIPPED ANOTHER DEFENDANT, THAT DEFENDANT PURCHASED COMPANY OPTIONS ON A DEFENDANT'S RECOMMENDATION, AND PAID A DEFENDANT A KICKBACK FROM HIS ILL-GOTTEN GAINS. WITHIN MOMENTS AFTER MEETING WITH A DEFENDANT, ONE OTHER DEFENDANT TRANSFERRED $400,000 FROM A COMMODITIES BROKERAGE ACCOUNT TO HIS BANK ACCOUNT AND PLACED A 40 SECOND PHONE CALL TO MCKEE. AFTER THE PHONE CALL FROM OTHER DEFENDANT, MCKEE ALMOST IMMEDIATELY PURCHASED 500 SHARES OF COMPANY STOCK, A STOCK HE HAD NEVER PREVIOUSLY PURCHASED. WITHIN A FEW HOURS, OTHER DEFENDANT HAD OPENED A BROKERAGE ACCOUNT, TRANSFERRED THE $400,000 INTO HIS NEW BROKERAGE ACCOUNT, AND MADE HIS FIRST STOCK PURCHASE IN TEN YEARS BY PURCHASING 20,000 SHARES OF COMPANY. THE FOLLOWING DAY, OTHER DEFENDANT PURCHASED AN ADDITIONAL 10,000 SHARES AND THEN PURCHASED 241 SHORT TERM CALL OPTIONS IN COMPANY, INCREASING HIS [CONTINUED IN COMMENTS]",
